# Nmap Basics (Complete Human Notes)

## Introduction

Nmap is one of the first and most important tools I learned in cybersecurity. It is mainly used for scanning networks to find open ports, running services, and sometimes system information like operating system details.

At the beginning, I just saw it as a scanning tool, but later I understood that it is mainly used in the **reconnaissance phase** of ethical hacking, where we try to understand the target before any further testing.

---

## Basic Idea

In Nmap, we usually scan a target machine using its IP address.

Example IP (lab use):

192.168.1.10


or in practice labs:

10.10.10.5


This IP represents the system we are trying to analyze.

---

## Basic Scan (First Command)


nmap 192.168.1.10


This is the simplest scan. It checks common ports on the target machine.

Example output:

22/tcp open ssh
80/tcp open http


My understanding:
This means the system is running SSH (remote login) and a web server.

---

## Service Version Detection


nmap -sV 192.168.1.10


This shows what software is running on open ports.

Example output:

22/tcp open ssh OpenSSH 8.2
80/tcp open http Apache 2.4.41


My understanding:
Now I can see not just services, but also their versions, which helps in vulnerability analysis.

---

## Operating System Detection


nmap -O 192.168.1.10


This tries to detect the operating system of the target.

Example output:

OS details: Linux 4.x or 5.x kernel


My understanding:
It is not always 100% accurate, but it gives a good idea of the system.

---

## Aggressive Scan


nmap -A 192.168.1.10


This is a full scan that includes:
- OS detection
- Version detection
- Script scanning
- Traceroute

My understanding:
This gives a complete view of the target but takes more time.

---

## Scan Specific Ports


nmap -p 22,80,443 192.168.1.10


This scans only selected ports.

My understanding:
Useful when I already know which services I want to check.

---

## Scan All Ports


nmap -p- 192.168.1.10


This scans all 65535 ports.

My understanding:
It takes time but helps find hidden services running on uncommon ports.

---

## SYN Scan (Stealth Scan)


nmap -sS 192.168.1.10


This sends SYN packets without completing full connection.

My understanding:
It is faster and less detectable, commonly used in penetration testing.

---

## UDP Scan


nmap -sU 192.168.1.10


This scans UDP services like DNS and DHCP.

My understanding:
It is slower than TCP scans but important because many services use UDP.

---

## Real Example Scenario

If I scan:


nmap -sV 10.10.10.5


And get result:

22/tcp open ssh OpenSSH 7.6
80/tcp open http Apache 2.4.29


My understanding:
- SSH is open → possible remote login access
- HTTP is open → web server is running

So this system has potential attack surfaces in SSH and web services.

---

## What I Learned

- Nmap is used for network reconnaissance
- IP address represents the target system
- Open ports show running services
- Service versions help identify vulnerabilities
- Scanning is the first step in ethical hacking

---

## Cybersecurity Importance

Nmap is widely used in:
- Reconnaissance
- Enumeration
- Vulnerability assessment
- Penetration testing
- Network security analysis
